li.p:
No.  The matrix A=\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
\vvec_1 \amp \vvec_2 \amp \ldots \amp \vvec_{10} \end{array}
\right] must have a column without a pivot position.
Therefore, any equation A\xvec=\bvec has infinitely
many solutions.

 We have

	  \begin{array}{rl}
	  a\vvec_1+b\vvec_2+c\vvec_3 \amp = a\vvec_1 +
	  b\vvec_2+c(-\vvec_1+2\vvec_2) \\
	  \amp =
	  (a-c)\vvec_1+(b+2c)\vvec_2\text{.}
	  \end{array}

 We have

	  \begin{array}{rl}
	  a\vvec_1+b\vvec_2+c\vvec_3 \amp = a\vvec_1 +
	  b\vvec_2+c(-\vvec_1+2\vvec_2) \\
	  \amp =
	  (a-c)\vvec_1+(b+2c)\vvec_2\text{.}
	  \end{array}

We see that
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp a \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp b \\ -2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp c \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 2 \amp 1 \amp a \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp b \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2a-4b+c \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
If the equation is consistent, we must have 2a-4b+c=0. The solution space is the plane defined by \vvec_1 and \vvec_2.
